03953nam a22006615i 9781501722257DE-B159720190925031139.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190925s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017222577 a10.7591/97815017222572doi  a(DE-B1597)535312  a(OCoLC)1121057578  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0210002bisacsh1 aBogel, Fredric V., eauthor.14aThe Difference Satire Makes :bRhetoric and Reading from Jonson to Byron /cFredric V. Bogel. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource :b2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Satire, Resistance, Theory -- t2. A Theory of Satiric Rhetoric -- t3. Jonson's Volpone: Dramatic Reversal and Satiric Doubleness -- t4. Swift's Poems: Satire, Contamination, Authority -- t5. Gay's The Beggar's Opera: Satire and Simile -- t6. Fielding's Jonathan Wild: "Doing Violence to Certain Words" -- t7. Byron's Beppo: Satire and Romantic Abbreviation -- t8. Satire and the Augustan Critique of the Category -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffering both the first major revision of satiric rhetoric in decades and a critical account of the modern history of satire criticism, Fredric V. Bogel maintains that the central structure of the satiric mode has been misunderstood. Devoting attention to Augustan satiric texts and other examples of satire-from writings by Ben Jonson and Lord Byron to recent performance art-Bogel finds a complicated interaction between identification and distance, intimacy and repudiation.Drawing on anthropological insights and the writings of Kenneth Burke, Bogel articulates a rigorous, richly developed theory of satire. While accepting the view that the mode is built on the tension between satirist and satiric object, he asserts that an equally crucial relationship between the two is that of intimacy and identification; satire does not merely register a difference and proceed to attack in light of that difference. Rather, it must establish or produce difference.The book provides fresh analyses of eighteenth-century texts by Jonathan Swift, John Gay, Alexander Pope, Henry Fielding, and others. Bogel believes that the obsessive play between identification and distance and the fascination with imitation, parody, and mimicry which mark eighteenth-century satire are part of a larger cultural phenomenon in the Augustan era-a questioning of the very status of the category and of categorical distinctness and opposition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Sep 2019) 4aEngland. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Horror & Supernatural.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501722257.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG